cc:Work.dc:title: Outline - Skin template for Mixxx
cc:Work.dc:description: Multi-resolution skin template for Mixxx 1.10+ , based on the original idea of Gianfe

text.tspan: Changes to these originals will affect the clones (exept the text on the buttons,
Iooks like Inkscapes Text clones are non editable beside from the font properties)
Use Shift+D to select the original if you selected a clone (see infobar on the buttom then)
The border marks the maximal size for a skin to fit with all supported Operating Systems (OS).
We subtracht 10 px for the horizonal window decoration and 30px for the taskbar in fullscreen mode
Remember: Mixxx is available for different OS's , Mixxx can not resize skins.
What is the "Safe zone" border good for?
Select a "Safe zone border" for your target resolution from the unlocked "Safe zone" layer,
goto FILE->DOCUMENT PROPERTIES and choose "Resize page to drawing or selection".
This way you will get the correct coordinates for the single elements when doing a web-export later on.
A new derivates name is like "Skinname""TargetDimensions"-"Videostandard"
Work from a copy of the Outline1024x600-XGA folder.
Check Object properties with CTRL+SHFT+O . Most objects have IDs matching to the skin.xml.
Knobs need to be renamed after export, use your OS's batch renamer here. Naming scheme is knob_rotaryX_sY (X=1,2 or 3 , Y=0-63)
So change something in the "Original styles" above and watch the clones change , then select the clones and
(batch) export bitmaps. Bitmaps should all get the correct names for instant use in skin.xml.
To get the over(active) state for buttons etc simply redo the step before and add a "_over" suffix to the filenames using your OS's batch renamer
You do not need "over" state ("active" state) bitmaps for Slider (Knobs/Background) & Knobs.
Export the single "background" layer alone to get the background image. Check the <Background> key in in skin.xml for naming.
When working with Inkscape to get the coordinates for Mixxx' skin.xml remember that Inkscape uses the inverted system ( 0=lower left).
You can work around that by grouping all elements and do a vertical flip for the moment.
